ScolarlyOutput

ScolarlyOutput is a small R Shiny app for creating and exporting a complete plot of your academic Google Scholar profile.

It only requires the full link to your Google Scholar profile (just copy it and paste it in the box), and it will create a plot with your name (as it appears on your Gsoogle Scholar profile) and two panels:

  1. Citations per publication (including h- and g-index)
  2. Number of publications and citations per year (including total number of citations)

Below is an example of the ScolarlyOutput UI showing a plot of my own profile:

ScolarlyOutput user interface

You can change an accent colour and filter publications.

Colour picker

Once you are happy, the plot can be exported to PNG, PDF, and even SVG format in case you want to edit it (the downloaded file will be named Scholar_profile.png, only changing the file extension depending in the format you selected).

The downloaded plot (in this case, as PNG) looks like this:

ScolarlyOutput plot example

This app uses the fantastic scholar R package to extract the info from your Google Scholar profile, and then several tidyverse packages (most notably ggplot2) to wrangle and plot these data.

How to run it

Sadly, the scholar package cannot be run from a server like shinyapps.io, so this app must be run locally in your computer with R installed.

However, running it is very easy: you can simply run the code below in R (please note that the shiny package must be installed):

#install.packages("shiny")
library(shiny)
runGitHub("ScolarlyOutput", "JDLeongomez")

Alternatively, you can always download the ScolarlyOutput repository, and run the app.R file.

Why I made this super small app

I originally wrote a script to download data from Google Scholar and make these plots for a particular version of my CV. However, several friends liked it and wanted to make plots of their own profiles (and be able to easily update them), so I decided to turn the code into a Shiny App for anyone to use.
